init_text:
Is It Selfish to Pursue Risky Sports Like Extreme Mountain Climbing?

Some sports, like extreme mountain climbing, are dangerous. Since there are varying degrees of risk in most, if not all, sports (such as the possibility of concussions, broken bones and even death), how does one decide where the line might be drawn between what is reasonable and what is not? Are some sports simply too dangerous to be called a sport?

---

In my opinion,

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: A sport gets played because it makes money for the owners.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: As long as the public will buy tickets, watch on TV, buy sports apparel, cheer them on as heroes and call their names from the stands,

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: The owners do not care whether their employees are alive or dead, so long as they make money.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: Although society may expect them to avoid activities that may result in their premature death, it is not our duty.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: When we see a wealthy 23-year old professional basketball player being carried on an air stretcher after rupturing a disk in his back,

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: If they are forced into retirement, then brace yourself for the movie deal.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: Aren’t some sports too dangerous to play?

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: The players are earning a living, and they may be willing to risk their lives, for better or worse.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: Without risk, there is no sport.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: As long as there is demand for high-risk athletes, there will be someone willing to take the chances.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: So long as profits exceed the risks, the high-risk sports will persist.
